\vspace{-10pt}
\begin{tabbing}
\phantom{References: }\= \\
To: \>Nathaniel Livesey, Bill Read, Paul Wagner, William Daffer\\
Subject: \>Radiative Transfer Equation and Finite-Element Method\\
From: \>Van Snyder\\
References: \h{wvs-072}, \h{wvs-081}, \h{wvs-093}\\
\end{tabbing}

\parindent 0pt \parskip 4pt

The radiative-transfer equation can be written

\begin{equation}\label{one}
\frac{\text{d} I(s)}{\text{d} s} = \alpha(s) \, ( B(s) - I(s) ) \,.
\end{equation}

If one multiplies by an arbitrary \emph{test function} $g(s)$ that is not
identically zero everywhere, and integrates through the atmosphere, one has

\begin{equation}\label{two}
\int_a^b g(s)\, \frac{\text{d} I(s)}{\text{d} s}\, \text{d} s =
\int_a^b g(s)\, \alpha(s) \, ( B(s) - I(s) )\, \text{d} s \,.
\end{equation}

A solution $I(s)$ of Equation (\ref{two}) is called a \emph{weak solution} of
Equation (\ref{one}). If one integrates the left-hand side by parts, the result
is

\begin{equation}
g(b) I(b) - g(a) I(a)
-\int_a^b \frac{\text{d}g(s) }{\text{d} s} \, I(s)\, \text{d} s =
\int_a^b g(s)\, \alpha(s) \, ( B(s) - I(s) )\, \text{d} s \,.
\end{equation}

This is called the \emph{Galerkin procedure}.

If one now uses the same function as the test function and as an approximation
for $I(s)$, say a $C^1$ cubic spline with knots on the pressure grid, one has

\begin{equation}\label{four}
g^2(b) - g^2(a)
-\int_a^b g(s)\, \frac{\text{d}g(s) }{\text{d} s}\, \text{d} s =
\int_a^b g(s) \,  \alpha(s) \, ( B(s) - g(s) )\, \text{d} s \,.
\end{equation}

This is called the \emph{Rayleigh-Ritz-Galerkin} or \emph{Finite Element}
method. The integral on the left-hand side can be written explicitly as a
sixth-order polynomial (assuming $g(s)$ is a cubic spline). The right-hand side
is a one-dimensional quadrature, instead of a two-dimensional quadrature with
the inner integral exponentiated. The result is a banded algebraic equation for
the spline coefficients. It ought to require less time to solve than Equation
(\ref{one}).

The variational equations, to compute derivatives with respect to mixing ratios
and temperature, which can be gotten from Equation (\ref{one}) by
differentiating with respect to a parameter and exchanging the order of
differentiation on the left-hand side (see part 7 in \h{wvs-093}), are of the
same form. In the form of Equation (\ref{four}), the only nonlinear parameter is
temperature (excluding species for which $\alpha(s)$ depends upon mixing ratio).
With so much of the problem being linear, a separable method such as variable
projection (see \h{wvs-072} and \h{wvs-081}) ought to be very effective. If a
temperature solution is gotten in an early phase, and then not included in later
phases, those later phases involve purely linear equations.

One usually thinks of the finite-element method as a method to solve partial
differental equations, but I see no reason why it would not work for ordinary
differential equations.

